Several minutes later, Ra finds himself circling over what appears to be a new cemetery.  He surveys the area, though he can see no sign of the enemy he seeks.  Eventually, his keen falcon eyes are drawn to an opening in a hillside to one side of the cemetery.

//I wonder if my people once buried our dead?  Before we began to commit our bodies to the stars?//  The idle thought is short lived as he focuses on what lies below.

//I guess I have a choice.  I can either walk the cemetery for clues, or check the cave.//

[[Walk the cemetery.|First Quest 2a]]

[[Check the cave.|First Quest 2b]]

Ra glides toward the village, barely gaining any attention until he lands in the midst of several people.

//Never get a second chance to make a first impression.//

And with that thought firmly in mind, he allows his own genetic code to assert itself, feathers pulling inward even as his body expands out to it's natural size.

The people around him look surprised, but nowhere near as shocked as he had originally expected them to be.  

//The do not seem troubled by my appearance.//

Ra hears the soft crack of a twig snapping right beside him.  He turns his head slightly and sees a dark skinned man looking back at him, a simple bow and arrow in his hand pointed directly at Ra, //It may be primitive, but it would still hurt, maybe even be fatal if the man makes a lucky shot.//

Lifting his hands, Ra tries to indicate to the man that he is unarmed, then tilts his head toward the village center meaningfully.

He sees the man nod slightly, then starts walking into the village, knowing full well that the warrior could pierce him with an arrow at any moment if he so chose.

Sighing inwardly, Ra's stride inevitably leads him to the village center.  All around him people are watching, but it's the curiosity of seeing a stranger in their midst, not the alarm of seeing something //alien// among them.

"Go get Abu Ogyinae,"  A man's voice comes from just over Ra's shoulder.  For a second he thinks the man is addressing him, but a moment later a second man that he had not noticed before darts into the village from his other side.  

Ra watches him go, seeing the swift man heading straight toward the cave he had seen before.

//The evil I seek lies there,//  He reflects.

As he waits, Ra allows his eyes to drift slowly over his surroundings, trying to take in every detail of the people and the village they live in.

//I see no sign of //their// taint among these people.  No deformities, no disfigurements, no other signs of corruption.//

//What am I missing?//

His darkening thou

Hours later, Ra sits in the cage.  Even though his child stopped savaging his body mere minutes after it attacked him, the damage it did was extensive.  Much of Ra's leg is a shredded mess on the ground around him, and his entire body has taken on a sickly pale shade.  More concerning however are the other changes.  Growths that do not belong on his body writhe and twitch.

//I have lost,//  Ra has to fight to keep his thoughts focused, even as mad voices babble in his mind.  He can feel his mind slipping, not loosing his memories, but twisting his perceptions and warping his thoughts.  

//All is lost,//  He thinks, feeling one final fleeting moment of sadness before he is truly lost.

END.



Or perhaps you would prefer to return to the Atet as if this never happened?

[[Return to the Atet.|Entering Sandbox.]]

Two days later, Ra sits on the bridge of the Atet, looking out the viewport toward the pyramids of Egypt that are being built.  

//I was down in those caves with Nyarlathotep for seven days.  How is that even possible?//  His eyes slide to Hathor who is working the controls of the Atet as they finish the trip home.  She glances at him, fear and sadness in her gaze.  He knew she was afraid for him, knew that whatever happened in the cave had shaken him to his core.

//I told her much of what happened, but not all.  She understands that the situation is dire, but I do not have the heart to tell her that all that has been done has been for naught.//

With a heavy sigh, Ra stands and turns toward the exit of the bridge.


